It is required when object creation is a time-consuming, and costly operation, so we create objects with 
the existing object itself to by copying the existing ones.

--The cloned object can modify only the required properties,avoiding the unnecessary changes to the original object.
--This approach saves time and system resources, especially when object creation is expensive or complex.
--The clone() method is simple way to implement ths pattern, but cloning logic depends on the specific business requirements.

Example:Consider a game char system where creating a char involves loading graphics, skills and configurations.
Instead of creating a new chAR from scratch every time:
clone an existing char
Modify attributes like name,weapon or level.
Now use the new customized char.


--Many modern applications use the Builder Pattern to improve flexibility and maintainability in object creation.

This is used in Game Engines.
--complex char or env object are cloned instead of being reinitialized.
This improves performances by avoiding costly setup during gameplay or runtimw.

COMPONENTS:
1.Prototype Interface/Abstract class: Deines the clone() method and sets a standard for all objects they can be cloned.
2.Concrete Prototype:Implemets the prototype interface or extends the abstract class to provide actual cloning behaviour.
3.Client:Uses the prototype to create new objects by calling the clone() method.
4.Clone method:Specifies how an object is copied  and is implememted by concrete prototypes.
